                <li><a href="#service-providers">Service Providers</a></li>
                <li><a href="#facades">Facades</a></li>
                <li><a href="#helpers">Helpers</a></li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Basics</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><a href="#routing">Routing</a></li>
                <li><a href="#controllers">Controllers</a></li>
                <li><a href="#middleware">Middleware</a></li>
                <li><a href="#validation">Validation</a></li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Database</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><a href="#loquent">Loquent ORM</a></li>
                <li><a href="#query-builder">Query Builder</a></li>
                <li><a href="#migrations">Migrations &amp; Schema</a></li>
            </ul>
            <h3>The Frontend</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><a href="#templating">Edge Templating</a></li>
                <li><a href="#localization">Localization</a></li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Security</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><a href="#authentication">Authentication</a></li>
                <li><a href="#security">CSRF &amp; CORS</a></li>
            </ul>
            <h3>Advanced</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><a href="#artisan">Artisan CLI</a></li>
                <li><a href="#http-client">HTTP Client</a></li>
                <li><a href="#process">The Lifecycle</a></li>
            </ul>
        </nav>
    </aside>

    <main>
        <!-- GETTING STARTED -->
        <section id="introduction">
            <h1>Introduction</h1>
            <p>Welcome to the official <span class="highlight">LaraNode</span> documentation. LaraNode is a Node.js framework crafted for developers who love the elegance of Laravel but want the speed and ecosystem of JavaScript.</p>
            <div class="feature-grid">
                <div class="feature-card">
                    <h4>🏛️ Expressive Architecture</h4>
                    <p>Designed to be a 1:1 mirror of Laravel's file structure and patterns.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="feature-card">
                    <h4>🧩 Dependency Injection</h4>
                    <p>Powerful Service Container at the heart of the framework.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="installation">
            <h2>Installation</h2>
            <p>Get started by creating your first LaraNode project using our CLI.</p>
            <pre><code># Install laranode-cli globally
npm install -g laranode-cli

# Create a new project
laranode new my-app</code></pre>
            <p>Alternatively, clone the skeleton directly:</p>
            <pre><code>git clone https://github.com/laranode/skeleton.git my-app
cd my-app
npm install
node artisan serve</code></pre>
        </section>

        <!-- ARCHITECTURE -->
        <section id="service-providers">
            <h2>Service Providers</h2>
            <p>Service Providers are the central place of all LaraNode application bootstrapping. Your own application, as well as all of LaraNode's core services, are bootstrapped via service providers. Every provider extends the base <code>ServiceProvider</code> class and has two methods: <code>register()</code> and <code>boot()</code>.</p>

            <h3>The Register Method</h3>
            <p>The <code>register()</code> method is for binding things into the service container. You should never attempt to register any event listeners, routes, or any other piece of functionality within <code>register()</code>.</p>
            <pre><code>const ServiceProvider = use('laranode/Support/ServiceProvider');

class AppServiceProvider extends ServiceProvider {
    register() {
        // Bind a singleton into the container
        this.app.singleton('analytics', function (app) {
            return new AnalyticsService(app.make('config').get('analytics'));
        });
    }
}</code></pre>

            <h3>The Boot Method</h3>
            <p>The <code>boot()</code> method is called after all providers have been registered. This is where you should register macros, event listeners, global helpers, or any other bootstrap logic.</p>
            <pre><code>const Http = use('laranode/Support/Facades/Http');

class AppServiceProvider extends ServiceProvider {
    boot() {
        // Register HTTP macros
        Http.macro('github', function () {
            return this.withBaseUrl('https://api.github.com')
                .withHeaders({ 'Accept': 'application/vnd.github.v3+json' });
        });

        // Register global helpers
        global.formatCurrency = (amount) => '$' + parseFloat(amount).toFixed(2);
    }
}</code></pre>

            <h3>RouteServiceProvider</h3>
            <p>The <code>RouteServiceProvider</code> (located at <code>app/Providers/RouteServiceProvider.js</code>) manages all route file loading. You can add custom route files here.</p>
            <pre><code>class RouteServiceProvider extends ServiceProvider {
    configureRoutes() {
        const router = this.app.make('router');

        // Web routes (session, CSRF)
        router.group({ middleware: ['web'] }, () => {
            this.loadRouteFile('routes/web.js');
        });

        // API routes (stateless, /api prefix)
        router.group({ prefix: '/api', middleware: ['api'] }, () => {
            this.loadRouteFile('routes/api.js');
        });

        // Custom route files
        router.group({ prefix: '/admin', middleware: ['web', 'auth'] }, () => {
            this.loadRouteFile('routes/admin.js');
        });
    }
}</code></pre>

            <h3>Registering Providers</h3>
            <p>All service providers are registered in the <code>providers</code> array within <code>config/app.js</code>. Framework providers load first, then your application providers.</p>
            <pre><code>// config/app.js
providers: [
    // Framework Service Providers...
    require(base_path('vendor/laranode/framework/src/Http/HttpServiceProvider')),
    require(base_path('vendor/laranode/framework/src/Foundation/Providers/RouteServiceProvider')),
    // ...

    // Application Service Providers...
    require(base_path('app/Providers/AppServiceProvider')),
    require(base_path('app/Providers/RouteServiceProvider')),
]</code></pre>
        </section>

        <section id="facades">
            <h2>Facades</h2>
            <p>Facades provide a static-like interface to services that are available in the application's service container. Think of them as convenient shortcuts — instead of manually resolving services from the container, you can call methods directly on the Facade class.</p>
            <pre><code>// All available Facades
const Route  = use('laranode/Support/Facades/Route');   // Routing
const Auth   = use('laranode/Support/Facades/Auth');     // Authentication
const DB     = use('laranode/Support/Facades/DB');       // Database
const Hash   = use('laranode/Support/Facades/Hash');     // Hashing
const Crypt  = use('laranode/Support/Facades/Crypt');    // Encryption
const Config = use('laranode/Support/Facades/Config');   // Configuration
const Log    = use('laranode/Support/Facades/Log');      // Logging
const Lang   = use('laranode/Support/Facades/Lang');     // Translation
const Http   = use('laranode/Support/Facades/Http');     // HTTP Client</code></pre>
            <p>Each Facade class resolves its underlying service from the IoC container. For example, <code>Http</code> resolves the HTTP client factory, so <code>Http.get()</code> calls <code>get()</code> on the resolved instance. This means you can use Facades anywhere — controllers, service providers, route files, etc.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="helpers">
            <h2>Global Helpers</h2>
            <p>LaraNode provides a set of global helper functions available everywhere — controllers, service providers, views, and even the CLI. No imports needed.</p>
            <pre><code>// Path helpers
base_path('config/app.js')       // /my-app/config/app.js
app_path('Models/User.js')       // /my-app/app/Models/User.js
config_path()                    // /my-app/config
database_path('migrations')      // /my-app/database/migrations
public_path('css/app.css')       // /my-app/public/css/app.css
resource_path('views')           // /my-app/resources/views
storage_path('logs')             // /my-app/storage/logs

// Configuration &amp; Environment
env('APP_DEBUG', false)          // Read .env variables
config('app.name', 'LaraNode')   // Read config values

// URL helpers
url('/users/1')                  // http://localhost:3333/users/1
asset('css/app.css')             // http://localhost:3333/css/app.css
route('login')                   // URL for named route 'login'

// Utilities
collect([1,2,3])                 // Create a Collection
use('laranode/Support/Facades/DB') // Resolve a module (like require)
dd(variable)                     // Dump &amp; die (debug)
dump(variable)                   // Dump (console.log)</code></pre>

            <h3>Custom Helpers</h3>
            <p>Register your own global helpers in <code>AppServiceProvider</code> or a dedicated <code>app/helpers.js</code> file. They will be available everywhere, including Edge views.</p>
            <pre><code>// app/helpers.js
global.formatCurrency = (amount) => '$' + parseFloat(amount).toFixed(2);
global.truncate = (str, len = 50) => str.length > len ? str.slice(0, len) + '...' : str;

// app/Providers/AppServiceProvider.js
boot() {
    require(base_path('app/helpers'));
}

// Then use anywhere, including views:
// &#123;&#123; formatCurrency(product.price) &#125;&#125;</code></pre>
        </section>

        <!-- BASICS -->
        <section id="routing">
            <h2>Routing</h2>
            <p>All LaraNode routes are defined in the <code>routes/</code> directory. Routes in <code>routes/web.js</code> are assigned the <code>web</code> middleware group (session, CSRF). Routes in <code>routes/api.js</code> are stateless and prefixed with <code>/api</code>. Route files are loaded by your <code>RouteServiceProvider</code>.</p>

            <h3>Basic Routes</h3>
            <pre><code>const Route = use('laranode/Support/Facades/Route');

// Closure route
Route.get('/welcome', (req, res) => 'Hello World');

// Controller route
Route.get('/profile', 'UserController&#64;show');
Route.post('/profile', 'UserController&#64;update');
Route.put('/users/{id}', 'UserController&#64;update');
Route.delete('/users/{id}', 'UserController&#64;destroy');</code></pre>

            <h3>Named Routes</h3>
            <p>Named routes allow you to generate URLs or redirects using <code>route('name')</code>.</p>
            <pre><code>Route.get('/login', 'AuthController&#64;showForm').name('login');

// Generate URL: route('login') => '/login'</code></pre>

            <h3>Route Groups</h3>
            <p>Route groups allow you to share attributes like middleware and URL prefixes across multiple routes.</p>
            <pre><code>Route.group({ prefix: '/admin', middleware: ['auth'] }, () => {
    Route.get('/dashboard', 'AdminController&#64;index');
    Route.get('/users', 'AdminController&#64;users');
});</code></pre>

            <h3>Route Parameters</h3>
            <p>LaraNode automatically parses route parameters and makes them available on <code>req.params</code>.</p>
            <pre><code>Route.get('/users/{id}', (req, res) => {
    return res.json({ userId: req.params.id });
});</code></pre>
        </section>

        <section id="controllers">
            <h2>Controllers</h2>
            <p>Controllers group related request handling logic into a single class. They reside in <code>app/Http/Controllers/</code>. All controllers extend the base <code>Controller</code> class.</p>
            <pre><code>const Controller = use('laranode/Routing/Controller/Controller');

class UserController extends Controller {
    // GET /users
    async index(req, res) {
        const users = await User.all();
        return res.view('users.index', { users });
    }

    // POST /users
    async store(req, res) {
        const user = await User.create(req.only(['name', 'email']));
        return res.redirect('/users');
    }

    // GET /users/:id
    async show(req, res) {
        const user = await User.findOrFail(req.params.id);
        await user.load('posts');  // Load relations before view
        return res.view('users.show', { user });
    }
}

module.exports = UserController;</code></pre>

            <h3>FormRequest Validation</h3>
            <p>Attach FormRequests to controller methods for automatic validation before the method runs.</p>
            <pre><code>class TodoController extends Controller {
    static get requests() {
        return {
            store: use('App/Http/Requests/StoreTodoRequest')
        };
    }

    // req.all() is already validated when this runs
    async store(req, res) {
        await Todo.create(req.all());
        return res.redirect('/');
    }
}</code></pre>
        </section>

        <section id="middleware">
            <h2>Middleware</h2>
            <p>Middleware provides a convenient mechanism for inspecting and filtering HTTP requests entering your application.</p>
            <pre><code>class EnsureTokenIsValid {
    async handle(req, res, next) {
        if (req.input('token') !== 'secret') {
            return res.redirect('home');
        }
        return next();
    }
}</code></pre>
        </section>

        <section id="validation">
            <h2>The Validation Engine</h2>
            <p>LaraNode features an extremely powerful, asynchronous validation engine completely matching Laravel's capabilities.</p>
            
            <h3>Validating FormRequests</h3>
            <p>The cleanest way to validate data is by utilizing FormRequests.</p>
            <pre><code>// In app/Http/Controllers/TodoController.js
static get requests() {
    return {
        store: use('app/Http/Requests/Todo/StoreTodoRequest')
    };
}

async store(req, res) {
    await Todo.create(req.all());
    return res.redirect('/');
}</code></pre>

            <h3>Validation Rules Reference</h3>
            <p>Below is a comprehensive list of all available validation rules.</p>

            <div class="rule-group">
                <div class="rule-card" id="rule-accepted">
                    <h4>accepted</h4>
                    <div class="meta">Boolean / Presence</div>
                    <p>The field under validation must be <code>true</code>, <code>"true"</code>, <code>1</code>, <code>"1"</code>, <code>"yes"</code>, or <code>"on"</code>.</p>
                    <pre><code>'terms' => 'accepted'</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="rule-card" id="rule-accepted_if">
                    <h4>accepted_if:anotherfield,value</h4>
                    <div class="meta">Conditional</div>
                    <p>The field under validation must be "accepted" if the another field is equal to a specified value.</p>
                    <pre><code>'terms' => 'accepted_if:is_adult,true'</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="rule-card" id="rule-active_url">
                    <h4>active_url</h4>
                    <div class="meta">String / Network</div>
                    <p>The field under validation must have a valid A or AAAA record according to the <code>dns.lookup</code> Node.js function.</p>
                    <pre><code>'website' => 'active_url'</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="rule-card" id="rule-after">
                    <h4>after:date</h4>
                    <div class="meta">Date</div>
                    <p>The field under validation must be a value after a given date.</p>
                    <pre><code>'start_date' => 'after:2025-01-01'</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="rule-card" id="rule-alpha">
                    <h4>alpha</h4>
                    <div class="meta">String</div>
                    <p>The field under validation must be entirely alphabetic characters.</p>
                    <pre><code>'name' => 'alpha'</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="rule-card" id="rule-boolean">
                    <h4>boolean</h4>
                    <div class="meta">Type</div>
                    <p>The field under validation must be able to be cast as a boolean. Accepted input are <code>true</code>, <code>false</code>, <code>1</code>, <code>0</code>, <code>"1"</code>, and <code>"0"</code>.</p>
                    <pre><code>'is_admin' => 'boolean'</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="rule-card" id="rule-confirmed">
                    <h4>confirmed</h4>
                    <div class="meta">Cross-Field</div>
                    <p>The field under validation must have a matching field of <code>{field}_confirmation</code>.</p>
                    <pre><code>'password' => 'required|confirmed'</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="rule-card" id="rule-current_password">
                    <h4>current_password</h4>
                    <div class="meta">Authentication</div>
                    <p>The field under validation must match the authenticated user's password.</p>
                    <pre><code>'old_password' => 'current_password'</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="rule-card" id="rule-date">
                    <h4>date</h4>
                    <div class="meta">Type</div>
                    <p>The field under validation must be a valid, non-relative date according to the <code>Date.parse</code> function.</p>
                    <pre><code>'birthday' => 'date'</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="rule-card" id="rule-distinct">
                    <h4>distinct</h4>
                    <div class="meta">Array</div>
                    <p>When validating an array, the field under validation must not have any duplicate values.</p>
                    <pre><code>'tags.*' => 'distinct'</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="rule-card" id="rule-email">
                    <h4>email</h4>
                    <div class="meta">String</div>
                    <p>The field under validation must be formatted as an email address.</p>
                    <pre><code>'email' => 'required|email'</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="rule-card" id="rule-exists">
                    <h4>exists:table,column</h4>
                    <div class="meta">Database</div>
                    <p>The field under validation must exist on a given database table.</p>
                    <pre><code>'user_id' => 'exists:users,id'</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="rule-card" id="rule-image">
                    <h4>image</h4>
                    <div class="meta">File</div>
                    <p>The file under validation must be an image (jpeg, png, bmp, gif, svg, or webp).</p>
                    <pre><code>'avatar' => 'image'</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="rule-card" id="rule-max">
                    <h4>max:value</h4>
                    <div class="meta">Size</div>
                    <p>The field under validation must be less than or equal to a maximum value. Strings, numerics, and arrays are evaluated in the same fashion as the <code>size</code> rule.</p>
                    <pre><code>'bio' => 'max:500'</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="rule-card" id="rule-min">
                    <h4>min:value</h4>
                    <div class="meta">Size</div>
                    <p>The field under validation must have a minimum value.</p>
                    <pre><code>'password' => 'min:8'</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="rule-card" id="rule-nullable">
                    <h4>nullable</h4>
                    <div class="meta">Utility</div>
                    <p>The field under validation may be <code>null</code>. This is particularly useful when validating primitive types such as strings and integers that can contain <code>null</code> values.</p>
                    <pre><code>'middle_name' => 'nullable|string'</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="rule-card" id="rule-numeric">
                    <h4>numeric</h4>
                    <div class="meta">Type</div>
                    <p>The field under validation must be numeric.</p>
                    <pre><code>'price' => 'numeric'</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="rule-card" id="rule-regex">
                    <h4>regex:pattern</h4>
                    <div class="meta">String</div>
                    <p>The field under validation must match the given regular expression.</p>
                    <pre><code>'slug' => 'regex:/^[a-z0-9-]+$/'</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="rule-card" id="rule-required">
                    <h4>required</h4>
                    <div class="meta">Presence</div>
                    <p>The field under validation must be present in the input data and not empty.</p>
                    <pre><code>'title' => 'required'</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="rule-card" id="rule-unique">
                    <h4>unique:table,column,ignoreId</h4>
                    <div class="meta">Database</div>
                    <p>The field under validation must not exist within the given database table.</p>
                    <pre><code>'email' => 'unique:users,email'</code></pre>
                </div>

                <div class="rule-card" id="rule-url">
                    <h4>url</h4>
                    <div class="meta">String</div>
                    <p>The field under validation must be a valid URL.</p>
                    <pre><code>'website' => 'url'</code></pre>
                </div>

                <p><em>...and dozens more including <code>prohibited</code>, <code>present</code>, <code>missing</code>, <code>ulid</code>, <code>uuid</code>, <code>mac_address</code>, etc. matching Laravel's exact behavior.</em></p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- DATABASE -->
        <section id="loquent">
            <h2>Loquent ORM</h2>
            <p>Loquent is our "Active Record" implementation. It makes interacting with your database as simple as writing English.</p>
            <pre><code>const Model = use('laranode/Database/Loquent/Model');

class User extends Model {
    static table = 'users'; // default
    static fillable = ['name', 'email', 'password'];

    posts() {
        return this.hasMany(use('App/Models/Post'), 'user_id');
    }
}

// Fetch all admins
const admins = await User.where('role', 'admin').get();</code></pre>

            <h3>Loading Relations</h3>
            <p>Use <code>with()</code> for eager loading at query time, or <code>load()</code> / <code>loadMissing()</code> to explicitly load relations on an existing model instance before passing to a view.</p>
            <pre><code>// Eager loading at query time (most efficient for lists)
const users = await User.with('posts', 'roles').get();

// Explicit loading on an instance (useful before views)
const user = await User.find(1);
await user.load('posts', 'roles');         // Always (re)loads from DB
await user.loadMissing('comments');        // Only loads if not loaded yet

// Then use in your view: &#123;&#123; user.posts &#125;&#125;, &#123;&#123; user.roles &#125;&#125;</code></pre>
        </section>

        <section id="query-builder">
            <h2>Query Builder</h2>
            <p>LaraNode's database query builder provides a convenient, fluent interface to creating and running database queries.</p>
            <pre><code>const DB = use('laranode/Support/Facades/DB');

const users = await DB.table('users')
    .where('votes', '>', 100)
    .get();</code></pre>

            <h3>Subquery Joins</h3>
            <p>Use <code>joinSub()</code>, <code>leftJoinSub()</code>, and <code>rightJoinSub()</code> to join against subqueries. Supports both simple and closure-based multi-condition joins.</p>
            <pre><code>// Build a subquery
const latestPosts = DB.table('posts')
    .select('user_id')
    .selectRaw('MAX(created_at) as last_post')
    .groupBy('user_id');

// Simple joinSub
const users = await DB.table('users')
    .joinSub(latestPosts, 'lp', 'users.id', '=', 'lp.user_id')
    .select('users.*', 'lp.last_post')
    .get();

// Closure-based multi-condition joinSub
await DB.table('users')
    .joinSub(latestPosts, 'lp', (join) => {
        join.on('users.id', '=', 'lp.user_id')
            .on('users.tenant_id', '=', 'lp.tenant_id')
            .where('lp.total', '>', 100);
    })
    .get();

// leftJoinSub / rightJoinSub
await DB.table('users')
    .leftJoinSub(orderTotals, 'summary', 'users.id', '=', 'summary.user_id')
    .get();</code></pre>

            <h3>Closure-Based Joins</h3>
            <p>Existing <code>join()</code>, <code>leftJoin()</code>, and <code>rightJoin()</code> also support closures for multiple ON conditions.</p>
            <pre><code>await User.join('posts', (join) => {
    join.on('users.id', '=', 'posts.user_id')
        .on('users.tenant_id', '=', 'posts.tenant_id')
        .where('posts.published', true)
        .whereNotNull('posts.title');
}).get();</code></pre>
        </section>

        <section id="migrations">
            <h2>Migrations & Schema</h2>
            <p>Migrations are like version control for your database, allowing your team to modify and share the application's database schema.</p>
            <pre><code>const Schema = use('laranode/Support/Facades/Schema');

async up() {
    await Schema.create('users', (table) => {
        table.id();
        table.string('email').unique();
        table.timestamps();
    });
}</code></pre>
        </section>

        <!-- THE FRONTEND -->
        <section id="templating">
            <h2>Edge Templating</h2>
            <p>Edge is LaraNode's Blade-like templating engine. Templates use the <code>.edge</code> extension and reside in <code>resources/views/</code>. Edge supports layouts, partials, control structures, and all global helper functions.</p>

            <h3>Layouts &amp; Sections</h3>
            <pre><code>&lt;!-- resources/views/layouts/app.edge --&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
&lt;head&gt;&lt;title&gt;&#64;yield('title') - &#123;&#123; config('app.name') &#125;&#125;&lt;/title&gt;&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
    &#64;yield('content')
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!-- resources/views/welcome.edge --&gt;
&#64;extends('layouts.app')
&#64;section('title', 'Home')
&#64;section('content')
    &lt;h1&gt;Welcome, &#123;&#123; user.name &#125;&#125;&lt;/h1&gt;
&#64;endsection</code></pre>

            <h3>Control Structures</h3>
            <pre><code>&#64;if(user.isAdmin)
    &lt;span&gt;Admin Badge&lt;/span&gt;
&#64;endif

&#64;foreach(posts as post)
    &lt;p&gt;&#123;&#123; post.title &#125;&#125;&lt;/p&gt;
&#64;endforeach

&#64;forelse(notifications as note)
    &lt;p&gt;&#123;&#123; note.message &#125;&#125;&lt;/p&gt;
&#64;empty
    &lt;p&gt;No notifications.&lt;/p&gt;
&#64;endforelse</code></pre>

            <h3>Helpers in Views</h3>
            <p>All global helpers (<code>config()</code>, <code>route()</code>, <code>url()</code>, <code>asset()</code>, and your custom helpers) are available directly in Edge templates.</p>
            <pre><code>&lt;link href="&#123;&#123; asset('css/app.css') &#125;&#125;" rel="stylesheet"&gt;
&lt;a href="&#123;&#123; route('login') &#125;&#125;"&gt;Login&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&#123;&#123; formatCurrency(product.price) &#125;&#125;&lt;/p&gt;</code></pre>

            <h3>Using Relations in Views</h3>
            <p>To access model relations in views, load them in your controller first using <code>with()</code>, <code>load()</code>, or <code>loadMissing()</code>. Once loaded, access them as properties.</p>
            <pre><code>// Controller
const user = await User.find(1);
await user.load('posts');
return res.view('users.show', { user });

// View: resources/views/users/show.edge
&#64;foreach(user.posts as post)
    &lt;p&gt;&#123;&#123; post.title &#125;&#125;&lt;/p&gt;
&#64;endforeach</code></pre>
        </section>

        <section id="localization">
            <h2>Localization</h2>
            <p>LaraNode's localization features provide a convenient way to retrieve strings in various languages.</p>
            <pre><code>// resources/lang/en/messages.js
module.exports = {
    welcome: 'Welcome'
};

// In view
&#123;&#123; __('messages.welcome') &#125;&#125;</code></pre>
        </section>

        <!-- SECURITY -->
        <section id="authentication">
            <h2>Authentication</h2>
            <p>LaraNode provides both session-based web authentication and Sanctum-style API token authentication out of the box.</p>

            <h3>Session Authentication (Web)</h3>
            <pre><code>// Protect routes with auth middleware
Route.group({ middleware: ['auth'] }, () => {
    Route.get('/dashboard', 'DashboardController&#64;index');
});

// Access the authenticated user
async index(req, res) {
    const user = req.user;
    return res.view('dashboard', { user });
}</code></pre>

            <h3>API Token Authentication (Sanctum-style)</h3>
            <pre><code>const HasApiTokens = use('laranode/Auth/Traits/HasApiTokens');

class User extends HasApiTokens(Model) {
    static table = 'users';
}

// Create a token
const token = await user.createToken('api-token');
return res.json({ token: token.plainTextToken });

// Protect API routes
Route.group({ middleware: ['auth:api'] }, () => {
    Route.get('/user', (req, res) => res.json(req.user));
});
// Header: Authorization: Bearer 1|abc123...</code></pre>

            <h3>Hashing &amp; Encryption</h3>
            <pre><code>const Hash  = use('laranode/Support/Facades/Hash');
const Crypt = use('laranode/Support/Facades/Crypt');

// Hash a password
const hashed = await Hash.make('my-password');
const valid  = await Hash.check('my-password', hashed); // true

// Encrypt / Decrypt
const encrypted = Crypt.encrypt('sensitive-data');
const decrypted = Crypt.decrypt(encrypted);</code></pre>
        </section>

        <section id="security">
            <h2>CSRF &amp; CORS</h2>
            <p>LaraNode includes middleware to protect your application from cross-site request forgery and manage cross-origin resource sharing.</p>

            <h3>CSRF Protection</h3>
            <p>All POST/PUT/DELETE routes in the <code>web</code> middleware group are automatically protected. Use the <code>&#64;csrf</code> directive in your forms.</p>
            <pre><code>&lt;form method="POST" action="/submit"&gt;
    &#64;csrf
    &lt;input name="title" /&gt;
    &lt;button type="submit"&gt;Submit&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;</code></pre>

            <h3>CORS</h3>
            <pre><code>// config/cors.js
module.exports = {
    paths: ['api/*'],
    allowed_methods: ['*'],
    allowed_origins: ['https://yourfrontend.com'],
    allowed_headers: ['Content-Type', 'Authorization'],
};</code></pre>
        </section>

        <!-- ADVANCED -->
        <section id="artisan">
            <h2>Artisan CLI</h2>
            <p>Artisan is the command-line interface included with LaraNode. It provides a number of helpful commands that can assist you while you build your application. You can run any command using <code>node artisan</code>.</p>

            <h3>Development</h3>
            <pre><code># Start the development server
node artisan serve

# List all registered routes
node artisan route:list</code></pre>

            <h3>Make Commands (Code Generators)</h3>
            <p>Generate boilerplate files for your application with the <code>make</code> commands.</p>
            <pre><code># Generate a controller
node artisan make:controller UserController

# Generate a model
node artisan make:model Post

# Generate middleware
node artisan make:middleware EnsureAdmin

# Generate a migration
node artisan make:migration create_posts_table

# Generate a database seeder
node artisan make:seeder UserSeeder

# Generate a form request
node artisan make:request StorePostRequest

# Generate an API resource
node artisan make:resource UserResource

# Generate a custom artisan command
node artisan make:command SendEmails

# Generate a validation rule
node artisan make:rule Uppercase</code></pre>

            <h3>Database Commands</h3>
            <pre><code># Run pending migrations
node artisan migrate

# Rollback the last batch of migrations
node artisan migrate:rollback

# Drop all tables and re-run all migrations
node artisan migrate:fresh

# Seed the database
node artisan db:seed</code></pre>

            <h3>Queue &amp; Scheduling</h3>
            <pre><code># Process queued jobs
node artisan queue:work

# Run scheduled tasks
node artisan schedule:run</code></pre>

            <h3>Custom Commands</h3>
            <p>Create your own commands in <code>app/Console/Commands/</code>. They are automatically registered when placed in that directory.</p>
            <pre><code>// app/Console/Commands/SendEmails.js
const Command = use('laranode/Foundation/Console/Command');

class SendEmails extends Command {
    get signature() {
        return 'emails:send';
    }

    get description() {
        return 'Send queued emails to all users';
    }

    async handle() {
        this.info('Sending emails...');
        // Your logic here
        this.info('Done!');
    }
}

module.exports = SendEmails;</code></pre>
        </section>

        <section id="http-client">
            <h2>HTTP Client &amp; Macros</h2>
            <p>LaraNode features an expressive HTTP client powered by native <code>fetch</code>, accessible via the <code>Http</code> Facade. It provides a fluent API for making HTTP requests to external services.</p>

            <h3>Making Requests</h3>
            <pre><code>const Http = use('laranode/Support/Facades/Http');

// Basic requests
const response = await Http.get('https://api.github.com/users/octocat');
const data = await Http.post('https://api.example.com/users', { name: 'John' });

// Fluent configuration
await Http.withHeaders({ 'X-Custom': '123' })
    .withToken('super-secret-token')
    .acceptJson()
    .get('/endpoint');

// File uploads (multipart/form-data)
await Http.attach('avatar', fileBuffer, 'image.png')
    .post('/upload');</code></pre>

            <h3>HTTP Macros</h3>
            <p>Register reusable HTTP client configurations as macros in your <code>AppServiceProvider</code>, then use them anywhere — controllers, services, artisan commands, etc.</p>
            <pre><code>// app/Providers/AppServiceProvider.js
boot() {
    Http.macro('github', function () {
        return this.withBaseUrl('https://api.github.com')
            .withHeaders({ 'Accept': 'application/vnd.github.v3+json' });
    });
}

// In your controller or service
const response = await Http.github().get('/users/Sabbir1993');</code></pre>
        </section>

        <section id="process">
            <h2>The Lifecycle</h2>
            <p>Understanding the LaraNode request lifecycle is key to building complex applications.</p>
            <ol>
                <li>Request enters <code>index.js</code> (or <code>server.js</code>)</li>
                <li>Application is bootstrapped via <code>bootstrap/app.js</code></li>
                <li>Service Providers are registered (<code>register()</code> methods)</li>
                <li>Service Providers are booted (<code>boot()</code> methods)</li>
                <li>HTTP Kernel handles the incoming request</li>
                <li>Global Middleware executes (session, CSRF, CORS, etc.)</li>
                <li>Route is resolved &amp; route-level Middleware executes</li>
                <li>Controller method handles the request</li>
                <li>Response is sent back to the client</li>
            </ol>
        </section>
    </main>

    <script>
        // Simple scroll spy for active nav links
        window.addEventListener('scroll', () => {
            const sections = document.querySelectorAll('section');
            const navLinks = document.querySelectorAll('nav a');
            
            let current = '';
            sections.forEach(section => {
                const sectionTop = section.offsetTop;
                if (scrollY >= sectionTop - 150) {
                    current = section.getAttribute('id');
                }
            });

            navLinks.forEach(link => {
                link.classList.remove('active');
                if (link.getAttribute('href') === `#${current}`) {
                    link.classList.add('active');
                }
            });
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
